@The X-Phile

I hear you, and as a constructor myself it really pains me when I feel I am criticizing a constructor, and try to convey my appreciation for what they do regardless. As I said this would have been a fine Monday or Tuesday and even though the constructors envisioned it for April Fools it didn’t need to be. But on top of that the clueing was void of imagination or cleverness which is also not the constructors’ fault—I’m sure many of the clues are not their own. I can understand that the editors may have felt that they needed more straightforward down clues since the themers were virtually unclued—but still there’s no fun in essentially a typing contest where you fill in the down clues and the theme is basically spelled out.
To answer your question—yes I believe that there are cleverer puzzles that are rejected because they are a little too twisty for today’s tastes, even if they need some more refinement which the editors could encourage. And I 100 percent believe that the editors are deliberately making the clues more straightforward for commercial reasons and may not be happy about it themselves. I can’t imagine that Steve Ezersky and Ian Livengood, responsible for some of the cleverest, most devious, more tortuous puzzles in history are sitting there happy to clue ORES as “mine finds” and ARE as “how ___ you?” not to mention the other gimmes. But there you have it, they are, and I just would like an explanation.

